[[File:Johnstrup.png|thumb|upright|Frederik Johnstrup.]]
Professor '''Johannes Frederik Johnstrup''' (12 March 1818, in [[Christianshavn]], [[Denmark]] &ndash; 31 December 1894) was a [[Danish people|Danish]] [[Geology|geologist]] and [[Paleontology|paleontologist]]. He was the founder of [[Meddelelser om Grønland]].<ref name="Notes ">{{cite journal|last=Noe-Nygaard|first=A. |author2=C. Vibe |author3=[[Tyge W. Böcher|T. W. Böcher]] |author4=[[Erik Holtved|E. Holtved]]|title=Notes on Danish Scientific Work since 1939|journal=Arctic|volume=4|issue=1|pages=50|url=http://pubs.aina.ucalgary.ca/arctic/Arctic4-1-50.pdf|doi=10.14430/arctic3935}}</ref>

Johnstrup received his Bachelor of Science in 1844.  He became an associate professor of [[mineralogy]] and [[natural science]] at the [[Sorø Academy]] in 1846. When the academy closed in 1848, he became assistant lecturer in [[Kolding]].  Three years later, he taught in [[Sorø]] and in 1866, he became professor of mineralogy and geology at the [[University of Copenhagen]] and the [[Technical University of Denmark|Polytechnic Institution]].

In 1876, he led an expedition to [[Iceland]] to study [[Askja]] and the volcanoes at [[Mývatn]] with [[Þorvaldur Thoroddsen]] as his guide.<ref>Hintze, V. ''[http://runeberg.org/dbl/6/0323.html Thoroddsen, Thorvaldur] entry in [[Carl Frederik Bricka|C. F. Bricka]] (ed.): ''[[Dansk biografisk lexikon]]: tillige omfattende Norge for Tidsrummet 1537–1814''; Gyldendal, Copenhagen 1887&ndash;1905; vol. XVII (1903), pp 283-5.</ref>

In 1878, with Heinrich Rink, Johnstrup founded the governmental institution, [[Commission for Scientific Investigations in Greenland|Commission for the Direction of Geological and Geographical Investigations in Greenland]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Bravo|first=Michael|author2=Sverker Sörlin|title=Narrating the Arctic: a cultural history of Nordic scientific practices|publisher=Science History Publications|date=2002 |pages=238|isbn=0-88135-385-X|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6wjlteumklQC&pg=PA238 }}</ref> Ten years later, he led the Danish Geological Survey. He developed Denmark's Mineralogical Museum, and led the construction of a new building in 1893.

Johnstrup authored a number of treatises by which he greatly promoted the understanding of Denmark's geological conditions, particularly the glacial phenomena. In 1894, he became an honorary doctorate at the University.

