{{Science}}

This is a glossary of terms used in [[speciation]] research and related [[evolution]]ary disciplines. It is intended as introductory material and a structured organization of the often complex language used in the literature. Related glossaries in biology are: the [[glossary of biology]], [[glossary of genetics]], [[glossary of ecology]], and the [[glossary of botany]].

{{glossary}}

==A==
{{term |1=Agamospecies}}
{{defn |1=A species that does not reproduce sexually but instead by cloning.<ref>{{Citation|author=Oxford Reference |title=agamospecies |publisher=Oxford University Press |date=2008 |url= }}</ref> Agamospecies are sometimes represented by [[species complex]]es that contain some [[Ploidy|diploid]] individuals and other [[Apomixis|apomitic forms]]—in particular, plant species that can reproduce via [[agamospermy]].<ref name="Coyne&Orr2004">{{Citation | title=Speciation | author1=Jerry A. Coyne |author1link=Jerry Coyne |author2=H. Allen Orr |author2link=H. Allen Orr | date=2004 | pages=1–545 | publisher=Sinauer Associates | isbn=0-87893-091-4 }}</ref>}}

{{term |1=Allochronic isolation}}
{{defn |1=Isolation of two populations of a species due to a change in breeding periods. This isolation acts as a precursor to '''allochronic speciation''', speciation resulting from two populations of a species that have become isolated due to differences in breeding periods. An example is the periodical 13- and 17-year ''[[Magicicada]]'' species.<ref name="Coyne&Orr2004"/>}}

{{term |1=Allo-parapatric speciation}}
{{defn |1=A mode of speciation where divergence occurs in allopatry and is completed upon [[secondary contact]] of the populations--effectively a form of [[reinforcement (speciation)|reinforcement]].<ref>{{Citation |title=Sympatric speciation in animals: new wine in old bottles |author=Guy L. Bush |journal=Trends in Ecology & Evolution |year=1994 |volume=9 |issue=8 |pages=285–288 |doi=10.1016/0169-5347(94)90031-0}}</ref><ref name="Coyne&Orr2004"/>}}

[[File:Allopatric Speciation Schematic.svg|right|thumb|upright=1.3|In allopatric speciation, a population becomes separated by a geographic barrier. [[Reproductive isolation]] evolves, resulting in two separate species.]]
{{term |1=[[Allopatric speciation]]}}
{{defn |1=A mode of speciation where the evolution of reproductive isolation is caused by geographic separation of a species population.<ref name="eLS2003">{{cite journal | last =Howard | first =Daniel  J. | title =Speciation: Allopatric  | journal =eLS | publisher =John Wiley & Sons Ltd | location =Chichester | date =2003 | url =http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1038/npg.els.0001748/abstract | doi =10.1038/npg.els.0001748}}</ref> Also called '''geographic speciation''', '''vicariance''',  '''vicariant speciation''', or '''dichopatric speciation'''.}}

