==K==
[[File:Kaneshiro Peripatric Speciation (process).png|right|thumb|upright=1.3|In the Kaneshiro model of [[peripatric speciation]], a sample of a larger population results in an isolated population with less males containing attractive traits. Over time, choosy females are selected against as the population increases. [[Sexual selection]] drives new traits to arise (green), reproductively isolating the new population from the old one (blue).]]
{{term |1=Kaneshiro model}}
{{defn |1=A model of [[peripatric speciation]] developed by Kenneth Y. Kanneshiro where a [[Sexual reproduction|sexual species]] experiences a population bottleneck—that is, when the genetic variation is reduced due to small population size—[[Mate choice|mating discrimination]] among females may be altered by the decrease in [[Courtship display|courtship behaviors]] or displays of males. This allows sexual selection to give rise to novel sexual traits in the new population.<ref>{{Citation |title=Sexual selection and peripatric speciation: the Kaneshiro model revisited |author=Anders Ödeen & Ann-Britt Florin |journal=Journal of Evolutionary Biology |year=2002 |volume=15 |issue= |pages=301–306 |doi=10.1046/j.1420-9101.2002.00378.x}}</ref>}}

