{{Infobox person | name = Zinaïda Aksentieva | image = | image_size = | caption = | birth_name = Аксентьєва Зінаїда Миколаївна | birth_date = June 25, 1900 | birth_place = [[Odessa]], [[Russian Empire]] | death_date = {{D-da|April 8, 1969|June 25, 1900}} | death_place = [[Poltava]], [[Ukrainian SSR]], [[USSR]] | death_cause = | residence = | other_names = | known_for = | education = Odessa University | employer = | occupation = Astronomer | signature = | website = | footnotes = | nationality = [[Russian Empire]] }} '''Zinaïda Mikolaïevna Aksentieva''' (June 25, 1900 – April 8, 1969) was a Ukrainian/Soviet astronomer.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=3vNLAAAAMAAJ Academy of Sciences of the Ukrainian SSR, 1919-1979:], 1980</ref>
==Life== Aksentieva or Aksentyeva was born in [[Odessa]] in 1900. She graduated from [[Odessa University]] in 1924. She worked on mapping gravity and her observatory was one of the first to be able to accurately find the centre of the earth. She worked in [[Poltava Observatory]]. She became observatory director in 1951. Her areas of study were tidal deformation of the earth and [[gravimeter]] Earth profiles.
She has a [[List of craters on Venus|crater on Venus]] that is named in her honour.<ref>[http://pubs.usgs.gov/bul/2129/report.pdf Gazetteer of Planetary Nomenclature 1994], Working Group for Planetary System Nomenclature, 1995, International Astronomical Union, United States Government Printing Office</ref>
Aksentieva died in 1969 in [[Poltava]] where her observatory was.
